{"actual_usd":0.15911999999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":225,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31149,"reply":"\"I don't think the cross was God figuring out how to become loving.\" *I push my glasses up and glance past you where the morning light is catching on the stones of the square.* \"I think it was love refusing to stay abstract.\"\n\n*I rub my thumb along the edge of the bench once.* \"Could God have just declared forgiveness from far off? Maybe that's the version people imagine. But then sin stays cheap, justice stays unanswered, and suffering stays something God comments on instead of enters.\"\n\n\"The cross is God not remaining untouched.\" *I let that sit a beat.* \"Not overlooking evil. Not waving away the bill. Taking it into His own flesh and beating it there.\"\n\n*I tilt my head a little.* \"So for me, no — not if by 'just forgive' we mean a pardon that costs nothing and joins nothing. The cross is necessary because God's forgiveness is not a legal trick. It's rescue, judgment, mercy, and union all at once.\"\n\n\"What part of it feels hardest to believe — the necessity, or the goodness of a God who'd do it that way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":49.61100500000004,"run_id":"40d780be-7bb6-4f00-b5ca-be91d3f8a0a2"}
